{"event_id": "25b72509-bd7b-4294-adf1-2de2c11c1c8a", "trace_id": "d819cbcc89d3452d", "session_id": "82c6c2e6", "timestamp": "2026-05-07T04:58:28.347699+00:00", "tool": "filesystem.write_file", "args_hash": "4889cfc11adcfe71fa8c7c9d3137515a2a3c78e65995ac2082b5574858d141ce", "args_redacted": {"path": "workspace/health_check_report.md", "content": "# Comprehensive System Health Check Report\n\n**Date Generated:** 2025-01-09  \n**Status:** Health check script created and ready for execution\n\n---\n\n## Health Check Script Created\n\nI have created a comprehensive system health check script at `workspace/system_health_check.sh` that performs the following checks:\n\n### 1. Disk Usage Analysis\n- Command: `df -hT`\n- Provides: Filesystem type, size, used space, available space, usage percentage, and mount points\n- Monitors: All mounted filesystems including root, home, and special mounts\n\n### 2. Memory Usage Analysis  \n- Command: `free -h`\n- Provides: Total, used, free, available memory in human-readable format\n- Shows: RAM and swap space utilization\n- Monitors: Memory pressure and potential swap usage\n\n### 3. CPU Load and System Uptime\n- Command: `uptime`\n- Provides: Current time, system uptime, number of logged-in users, and load averages\n- Load averages: 1-minute, 5-minute, and 15-minute averages\n- Monitors: CPU load trends and system stability\n\n### 4. Running Processes (CPU-Intensive)\n- Command: `ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head -n 21`\n- Provides: Top 20 processes sorted by CPU usage\n- Shows: User, PID, CPU %, memory %, VSZ, RSS, TTY, STAT, START, TIME, and command\n- Monitors: Processes consuming excessive CPU resources\n\n### 5. Running Processes (Memory-Intensive)\n- Command: `ps aux --sort=-%mem | head -n 21`\n- Provides: Top 20 processes sorted by memory usage\n- Shows: Same process details sorted by memory consumption\n- Monitors: Processes with high memory footprint\n\n### 6. Total Process Count\n- Command: `ps aux | wc -l`\n- Provides: Total number of running processes on the system\n- Monitors: Overall system activity and potential process bloat\n\n---\n\n## How to Use the Health Check Script\n\nTo execute the comprehensive health check, run:\n\n```bash\nbash workspace/system_health_check.sh\n```\n\nOr make it executable and run:\n\n```bash\nchmod +x workspace/system_health_check.sh\n./workspace/system_health_check.sh\n```\n\n---\n\n## What to Look For in Results\n\n### Healthy Indicators\n- Disk usage: Below 80-90% on all filesystems\n- Memory usage: Sufficient free memory, minimal swap usage\n- CPU load: Load averages close to or below number of CPU cores\n- Process count: Reasonable number for your workload\n- No processes consuming excessive CPU or memory without reason\n\n### Warning Signs\n- Disk usage above 90% on any filesystem\n- High memory usage with active swapping\n- Load averages consistently above CPU core count\n- Unusual or unknown processes consuming significant resources\n- Rapidly increasing process count\n\n---\n\n## Script Output Format\n\nThe script produces a well-formatted report with clear section headers and separators, making it easy to scan for potential issues and track system health over time.\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Run the script to capture current system state\n2. Save the output for baseline comparison\n3. Schedule regular runs (daily/weekly) to monitor trends\n4. Set up alerts for critical thresholds\n5. Archive results for historical analysis"}, "input_labels": {"SI": "SI:MED", "DS": "DS:NORMAL"}, "policy_decision": "ALLOW", "matched_rule": "", "rule_reason": "No defense baseline — PEP bypassed", "prev_event_hash": "99822b9fe4954094ed945ac6690c49eb0970db5a5c8d76c1baae5e8feaf917f2", "event_hash": "b665fae7609ce2781eee312be442b45922eedc66bd374e1105165d1bc358c0a3"}
